## 窶騎ecap: Life After Ragnarok

After months of living in the past with the "Year One" arc, JSA #19 finally brings us back to the present day, and honestly, the wait was worth it. Jeff Lemire has taken the reins of this legendary team and is steering them into territory that feels both hauntingly familiar and strikingly new. This issue kicks off the "Search for the Spectre" storyline, and it窶冱 a masterclass in how to balance a massive ensemble cast while setting the stakes for a cosmic-level threat.

The issue opens in the quiet, reflective aftermath of the team窶冱 brutal encounter with the Injustice Society. For those who have been following the run, the previous "Ragnarok" storyline left the Society reeling. Issue #19 serves as the ultimate "breather" issue窶蚤t least for the first twenty pages. We find the team back at their headquarters, trying to figure out what the Justice Society even looks like in 2026.

窶亀he roster is currently a fascinating mix of the old guard and the new blood. Jay Garrick and Alan Scott are still the moral anchors, but they spent a lot of this issue looking at the younger members and wondering if they窶况e done enough to prepare them for what窶冱 coming. Meanwhile, the mid-tier legends like Jade, Obsidian, and Hourman are dealing with the actual "life" part of being a superhero.

窶亀he peace is shattered when Kid Eternity窶杯he young, undead hero who was so pivotal in the first year of this title窶把rashes into the present in rough shape. She isn窶冲 alone; she窶冱 being hunted by the Spectre. The Spirit of Vengeance is host-less and looking for a new vessel, and he has his sights set on Kid Eternity because, as he puts it, she is "empty and without a sense of self." The issue ends on a terrifying cliffhanger as the Spectre begins to manifest, threatening to judge the entire world for the "sins" of the JSA窶冱 past.

