## 窶輝acing: The Calm and the Storm

![](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d56e145f80b7500016ba502/39ccefa2-fd64-4cc9-8c4d-aac9f4b0a714/1000014947.jpg?format=original)

窶輝acing is always tricky with team books, especially when you have a roster this deep. However, #19 manages to feel breezy without feeling shallow. The first two-thirds of the book are dedicated to "living" with the characters. We get to see them in their downtime, which is essential for a book about a "family" like the JSA. If we don窶冲 care about them when they窶决e eating breakfast or arguing in the gym, we won窶冲 care when the Spectre tries to erase them from existence.

窶亀he transition from the "slice-of-life" moments to the horror of the Spectre窶冱 arrival is jarring in the best way possible. The tension ramps up slowly as Kid Eternity窶冱 arrival is preceded by a sense of dread that even Alan Scott窶冱 ring can窶冲 quite pinpoint. By the time the final splash page hits, the shift from "day in the life" to "end of the world" feels earned. If I had one complaint, it窶冱 that some of the dialogue in the transition scenes felt a little heavy on the recap. I understand we need to catch up new readers after the "Year One" arc, but for long-time pull-list fans, it felt a bit like an exposition dump in a few panels.

