## 窶帰rt: A New Visual Language

![](https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5d56e145f80b7500016ba502/73282125-4e0c-40e3-a7ba-27efc5076bc4/1000014948.jpg?format=original)

窶汽iego Olortegui is doing some incredible work here. Moving away from the moodier, more shadow-heavy art of the previous arc, Olortegui brings a kinetic, "classic superhero" feel to the book. His character designs are expressive窶輩ou can see the exhaustion in Jay Garrick窶冱 eyes and the bottled-up frustration in Rick Tyler窶冱 posture.

窶亀he action sequences, specifically the sparring match, have a great sense of flow. You can actually follow the physics of the movement, which is something a lot of modern artists struggle with. But the real standout is how he renders the Spectre. The Spectre should be terrifying, and Olortegui nails it. He doesn't just look like a guy in a green cape; he looks like a force of nature manifesting through the page.

窶記uis Guerrero窶冱 colors deserve a shout-out as well. The way he uses the vibrant greens of Alan Scott窶冱 construct energy to contrast with the sickly, ethereal glow of Kid Eternity creates a visual tension that perfectly matches the script. The colors pop during the daytime scenes at the brownstone, making the JSA窶冱 world feel lived-in and warm, which only makes the cold, dark arrival of the Spectre feel more intrusive.

